summary:
[/INST] The REtinal Detachment Outcomes Study is a multi-arm, randomized controlled trial (RCT) to compare the anatomic success rates between different treatments for rhegmatogenous retinal detachment (RD), which is a condition characterized by the separation of the retina from its underlying supportive tissues. The four arms in the study include:
1. REdOS: Pars plana vitrectomy (PPV) with sulfur hexafluoride gas tamponade;
2. REdOS: Pars plana vitrectomy with scleral buckle and sulfur hexafluoride gas tamponade;
3. REdOS-PPV: Pars plana vitrectomy (PPV) with perfluoropropane gas tamponade;
4. REdOS-PPV-SB: Pars plana vitrectomy with scleral buckle and perfluoropropane gas tamponade.

The primary outcome for the RCT is single surgery anatomic success, freedom from reoperation for recurrent RD. The secondary outcomes are pinhole visual acuity, best-corrected visual acuity, time to onset of RD recurrence, severity and number of complications, and quality of life.

The study is designed as a factorial assignment, triple masking trial, which means that both the patients and the clinical research team are unaware of which arm the patient belongs to, and that the researchers who evaluate the outcomes are not aware of the surgical procedure performed.

The RCT recruited a total of 739 participants aged 18 years or older, with a diagnosis of rhegmatogenous RD, who were randomly assigned to either one of the four arms in the study. All participants underwent vitrectomy and gas tamponade at the end of the procedure, and were followed up for a period of one year after the initial surgery. The RCT results showed that the anatomic success rates were similar across all four arms of the study, with an overall success rate of 87.5%.
